1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:19,254
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:19,234 --> 00:00:36,399
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Samma Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,418 --> 00:00:46,692
So we are continuing with the human condition and there are two pieces here that Bhikkhu Bodhi has chosen for us.

4
00:00:48,613 --> 00:01:17,828
pretty juicy stuff you know anyway this is Saka the ruler of the devas so in the scriptures the devas these gods coming from different realms would often approach the Buddha Saka is the ruler of a particular heaven a happy one and he asked the Buddha beings wish to live without hate harming hostility or enmity they wish to live in peace

5
00:01:18,061 --> 00:01:23,469
Yet they live in hate, harming each other, hostile and as enemies.

6
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:27,878
By what fetters are they bound, sir, that they live in such a way?

7
00:01:29,239 --> 00:01:41,941
And the Blessed One replied, Ruler of the Devas, it is the bonds of envy and niggardliness that bind beings, so that although they wish to live without hate, hostility and enmity,

8
00:01:42,478 --> 00:01:49,189
and to live in peace, yet they live in hate, harming one another, hostile, and as enemies.

9
00:01:50,712 --> 00:02:03,713
This was the Blessed One's reply, and Saka, delighted, exclaimed, So it is, Blessed One, so it is, fortunate one, though the Blessed One, through the Blessed One's answer, I have overcome my doubt and got rid of uncertainty.

10
00:02:05,477 --> 00:02:06,158
Can't finish yet.

11
00:02:08,212 --> 00:02:12,377
Then Saka, having expressed his appreciation, asked another question.

12
00:02:12,837 --> 00:02:15,722
But sir, what gives rise to envy and niggardliness?

13
00:02:16,122 --> 00:02:17,104
What is their origin?

14
00:02:17,183 --> 00:02:18,104
How are they born?

15
00:02:18,525 --> 00:02:19,425
How do they arise?

16
00:02:20,227 --> 00:02:22,389
When what is present, do they arise?

17
00:02:22,550 --> 00:02:25,073
And when what is absent, do they not arise?

18
00:02:26,253 --> 00:02:30,979
Envy and niggardliness, ruler of the Devas, arise from liking and disliking.

19
00:02:31,340 --> 00:02:32,701
This is their origin.

20
00:02:33,002 --> 00:02:35,264
This is how they're born, how they arise.

21
00:02:35,586 --> 00:02:36,986
When they're present, they arise.

22
00:02:37,568 --> 00:02:39,789
And when these are absent, they do not arise.

23
00:02:40,409 --> 00:02:43,433
But, sir, what gives rise to liking and disliking?

24
00:02:43,454 --> 00:02:47,377
They arise, O ruler of the Devas, from desire.

25
00:02:48,318 --> 00:02:50,159
And what gives rise to desire?

26
00:02:51,020 --> 00:02:53,644
It arises, ruler of the Devas, from thinking.

27
00:02:53,683 --> 00:02:58,127
When the mind thinks about something, desire arises.

28
00:02:58,508 --> 00:03:02,772
When the mind thinks of nothing, desire does not arise.

29
00:03:03,513 --> 00:03:05,876
But what gives rise to thinking?

30
00:03:06,676 --> 00:03:10,502
Thinking arises from elaborate perceptions and notions.

31
00:03:10,862 --> 00:03:14,927
When elaborate perceptions and notions are present, thinking arises.

32
00:03:15,389 --> 00:03:19,995
When elaborate perceptions and notions are absent, thinking does not arise.

33
00:03:21,957 --> 00:03:25,081
This evening you experienced all that in your sitting.

34
00:03:26,479 --> 00:03:28,483
So if we take this apart, you'll see.

35
00:03:29,043 --> 00:03:32,728
So Saka, he's come with this problem, right?

36
00:03:33,048 --> 00:03:38,074
He's asking, well, why is it that everybody does want to live in peace and we all end up killing each other?

37
00:03:38,955 --> 00:03:40,877
So he says, through envy and niggardliness.

38
00:03:41,498 --> 00:03:42,360
Envy and niggardliness.

39
00:03:42,379 --> 00:03:46,544
So it goes back to this original problem of greed, right?

40
00:03:46,564 --> 00:03:54,175
And greed, remember, greed is better to... Acquisitiveness is a better word, right?

41
00:03:54,661 --> 00:04:21,916
now remember that the fundamental problem is that believing ourselves to be human beings full stop our desire for happiness drives us to seek happiness in the phenomenal world in other words in what we experience so once you're into that search you begin to accumulate so the more money you've got in the bank the safer you feel now if somebody's got more see then you're envious

42
00:04:22,875 --> 00:04:26,442
And just to make a small distinction between envy and jealousy.

43
00:04:27,262 --> 00:04:29,065
So you can say to somebody, oh, I envy you.

44
00:04:29,245 --> 00:04:31,649
And they're rather proud of that.

45
00:04:31,790 --> 00:04:33,372
They're very happy that you should envy them.

46
00:04:33,653 --> 00:04:36,677
But if you say to somebody, I'm jealous of you, that stings a bit, doesn't it?

47
00:04:37,339 --> 00:04:40,545
So there's something added to envy that turns it into jealousy.

48
00:04:40,805 --> 00:04:42,767
And it's a sort of hatred, isn't it?

49
00:04:42,788 --> 00:04:46,233
You not only envy yourself, you're hating them for having what they've got.

50
00:04:47,327 --> 00:05:10,803
and that niggardliness means that even when somebody wants a bit of what you have you know you're not going to give it under no circumstance so as soon as you're into acquisitiveness as soon as you're into holding something you're into a conflict you can't you can't not be in conflict once you're grasping something once you're holding something tight

51
00:05:11,375 --> 00:05:24,456
You've got to obviously defend it from enemies, because remember, just as we're envious of others, they happen also to be envious of us, which means they want what we've got.

52
00:05:24,959 --> 00:05:54,375
so therefore you can see as soon as we have this wrong understanding as to where happiness is to be found we think that it's to do with accumulation of some sort accumulation of money of objects of friends see these are my friends you see my family then you're always immediately into some sort of conflict hence they live in hatred harming one another hostile and as enemies

53
00:05:55,738 --> 00:05:59,492
Now, when he asks, what's the cause of this?

54
00:05:59,533 --> 00:06:05,175
The Buddha goes right back to the fundamental position of liking and disliking.

55
00:06:14,487 --> 00:06:34,386
what's the cause of envy liking and disliking now liking and disliking refers to that point on the Buddhist psychology called dependent origination when we experience something as pleasant or unpleasant hmm

56
00:06:35,362 --> 00:06:40,651
So we're always, as soon as we experience something, we're always shifting it to one side or the other.

57
00:06:41,112 --> 00:06:47,322
We always find it nice, pleasant, or we find it not nice, not pleasant.

58
00:06:47,802 --> 00:06:51,649
So the whole, we live in a world of that fundamental duality.

59
00:06:51,882 --> 00:07:01,317
There's an area in the middle that we call neutral, but if you look at that closely enough, it just shades into what's likeable or shades into what's not likeable.

60
00:07:01,798 --> 00:07:06,185
So that's our fundamental experience of life.

61
00:07:06,204 --> 00:07:07,226
All beings have that.

62
00:07:07,867 --> 00:07:14,197
Even the mole, who is now again attacking our lawn, knows what is likeable and what is unlikable.

63
00:07:14,819 --> 00:07:17,382
And I definitely don't like the mole.

64
00:07:18,713 --> 00:07:24,721
But my heart goes out to it, feeling it from its position.

65
00:07:24,740 --> 00:07:32,009
So this liking and liking, now there's nothing wrong with that you see, because then he asks, well, what is the cause of that you see?

66
00:07:32,310 --> 00:07:35,434
So what happens after this liking and disliking?

67
00:07:36,935 --> 00:07:38,278
So it's desire, right?

68
00:07:38,298 --> 00:07:39,800
So that's the next thing, desire.

69
00:07:39,879 --> 00:07:42,223
Now what we mean by desire, you've got to be careful here.

70
00:07:42,608 --> 00:07:44,870
It's a desire based on wrong understanding.

71
00:07:44,930 --> 00:07:52,120
It's a desire which is coming from the misunderstanding as to where happiness is to be found.

72
00:07:53,901 --> 00:08:02,132
So what we get from that desire, often it's translated as craving, which is a bit strong really.

73
00:08:02,833 --> 00:08:08,358
But it's basically wanting what's likeable and not wanting what's unlikable.

74
00:08:08,920 --> 00:08:11,382
So immediately you're into an internal conflict.

75
00:08:11,767 --> 00:08:37,894
you're either holding on to something and pushing whatever is away that's a danger to you or you're resisting something which you don't like so already we're beginning the process of suffering we're beginning the process of hatred etc etc once we got that he asks what gives rise to desire so now here he talks about thinking

76
00:08:41,317 --> 00:08:43,039
See, when the mind thinks about something.

77
00:08:43,139 --> 00:08:49,570
So, there you are in your posture, you see, and suddenly you're in Acapulco.

78
00:08:50,571 --> 00:08:50,772
See?

79
00:08:51,172 --> 00:08:54,977
It's just arisen, the desire to get away, the desire to be on holiday.

80
00:08:55,238 --> 00:08:56,801
Off you go, you see.

81
00:08:56,821 --> 00:09:00,807
Or you remember something, something somebody said to you today which has irritated you, you see.

82
00:09:01,187 --> 00:09:01,707
So off you go.

83
00:09:01,729 --> 00:09:02,249
How could you?

84
00:09:02,690 --> 00:09:03,792
Who do you think you were?

85
00:09:06,615 --> 00:09:07,717
It's come from a thought, you see.

86
00:09:07,998 --> 00:09:08,538
Now,

87
00:09:09,092 --> 00:09:37,176
it says what gives rise to thinking okay so now we come to a rather it's it's a word which is difficult to translate in the Pali it's Papancha Papancha just means proliferation so it's a proliferation arising from a particular conditioning okay

88
00:09:38,049 --> 00:10:03,687
and it's because of these elaborated perceptions and notions that all these things come so if we were to go back on that instead of starting with you know the hatred and stuff that Saka is asking about here we have these conditionings within us and they're dormant they're like programs in a computer

89
00:10:04,054 --> 00:10:27,952
and then a button is pressed and a thought comes up right some idea comes up this idea is grasped by the mind and it's worked on it's worked on right but what's driving it is either this this desire see the desire either to get rid of what's unpleasant or to indulge what is pleasant

90
00:10:28,591 --> 00:10:35,062
So it's just another way of talking about the dependent origination, the psychology of the Buddha.

91
00:10:37,164 --> 00:10:45,659
So obviously the way out of that is to catch it at the moment of liking-disliking.

92
00:10:46,520 --> 00:10:53,653
So if we can be aware, if we can be awake and see the mind changing,

93
00:10:53,818 --> 00:11:20,990
determining something as likeable or dislikeable see there's not a problem because we can stay aloof from that and that's your position in meditation see so when you're sitting here like this you see and say a pain comes or discomfort comes you see to catch it at the point of discomfort see there's not a problem but as soon as you relate to it as not wanting it then you're in conflict with it see

94
00:11:21,577 --> 00:11:31,029
Now I'm not saying, we're not saying that if something really hurts that you can't move, but generally speaking, as soon as we get a little discomfort, off you go.

95
00:11:31,571 --> 00:11:33,113
Just watch yourself watching TV.

96
00:11:33,452 --> 00:11:40,140
See, just catch yourself constantly shifting and moving as the body just feels slight discomfort, off you go, you see.

97
00:11:40,160 --> 00:11:50,995
And it's this inability to be at peace with, equanimous with what is discomfort that is creating all this resistance in the psyche, you see.

98
00:11:51,514 --> 00:12:21,504
and so whenever something taps into that off you go hatred and all that sort of stuff so this is why we live in hate you see harming one another hostile and as enemies so it's a case of catching it right at the beginning where the liking and disliking arises and then just catching that wanting not wanting see and then just allowing that to pass away

99
00:12:22,970 --> 00:12:24,893
And that's how you remain at an even keel.

100
00:12:25,494 --> 00:12:27,756
When something is wholesome, of course, that's not a problem.

101
00:12:27,996 --> 00:12:34,986
When something is to our benefit, coming from the heart of goodwill and all that, then we should empower it.

102
00:12:35,346 --> 00:12:36,389
That's not a problem.

103
00:12:36,850 --> 00:12:44,821
It's those things which are based on not liking, those things based on a wrong desire.

104
00:12:45,321 --> 00:12:49,246
Seeking happiness in the sensual world.

105
00:12:49,267 --> 00:12:50,749
Real happiness, that is.

106
00:12:52,889 --> 00:12:56,653
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

107
00:12:57,174 --> 00:13:04,705
May you, by your careful discrimination, exit from all suffering sooner rather than later.

108
00:13:09,792 --> 00:13:13,496
Thank you very much.

